The swelling ratio of the hydrogel within 24 h was characterized by testing the mass change of the hydrogel. The prepared hydrogel sample (15 mm in diameter and 10 mm in height) was immersed in a tube containing 20 mL of PBS (pH 7.4). It was cultured in a shaker (37 ℃, 70 rpm). After the hydrogel was cultured to a specific time (1 h, 2 h, 3 h, 6 h, 12 h, 24 h), it was taken out. The surface moisture was immediately absorbed with filter paper. The weight (WS
                        ) of the hydrogel was measured. The water-swelling hydrogel was then freeze-dried. And the weight (WD
                        ) of the dry gel was obtained. The formula for calculating the swelling ratio was as follows: (WS-WD)/WD
                        .

The degradation behavior of hydrogel in vitro was evaluated by measuring the mass loss of hydrogel. The hydrogels (15 mm in diameter and 10 mm in height) were weighed (W0
                        ) and immersed in a tube containing 20 mL PBS. When the hydrogel was taken out at fixed time, it was weighed (Wt
                        ) after the surface moisture was immediately absorbed with the filter paper. The remaining mass of hydrogel was calculated by following formula: 1-(W0
                        -Wt
                        )/W0
                        . The hydrogel mass was set as the x-axis and plotted against the degradation time, and then the curve was differentiated. When the hydrogels were degraded for 7 days and 14 days, they were taken out and freeze-dried. Then the morphology was photographed by SEM to observe the changes of the microstructure of the hydrogel.

As previously mentioned [32], hydrogels were prepared in 96-well plate and washed with PBS (pH 7.4). Blood was obtained from healthy volunteer. The collection procedure of red blood cells (RBCs) complied with relevant laws and institutional guidelines. RBCs were centrifuged (RCF 1500 g) for 5 min and rinsed twice with PBS (pH 7.4). They were then suspended in PBS to obtain a 5% (v/v) suspension. RBCs suspension (100 μL) was added to the surface of the hydrogel or to the blank wells. RBCs suspension treated with double-distilled water and PBS (pH 7.4) was respectively positive control (AH2O
                        , 100% hemolysis) and negative control (APBS
                        , 0% hemolysis). The RBCs on the hydrogel were incubated at 37 ℃ for 1 h, and then centrifuged (RCF 1500 g) for 10 min after 900 μL of PBS (pH 7.4) was added. The supernatant (100 μL) was transferred to the cuvette and the absorption value (AS
                        ) was recorded at 576 nm by an UV–vis spectrophotometer. Hemolytic activity was determined by measuring the amount of hemoglobin that leaks out of the solution due to cytolysis. The hemolysis rate was calculated as [(AS
                         – APBS
                        ) / (AH2O
                         – AS
                        ) × 100] %, in which AS
                         is absorbance of the hydrogel group. Besides, after incubation, 10 μL RBCs suspension of each group was diluted with 90 μL PBS (pH 7.4) and transferred to a 96-well plate. The morphology of RBCs was obtained with an Olympus BX51 microscope.
